{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600657"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15629"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15629"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.11,0.15,0.07,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70420"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8320"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15629"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55884"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8649"},{"type":"tags","id":"8659"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20076"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70420"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, a gelatinous structure forms within each intervertebral disc. This structure persists throughout life and helps maintain disc flexibility and height.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following embryological structures gives rise to the nucleus pulposus of the intervertebral disc?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Notochord","Paraxial mesoderm","Intermediate mesoderm","Lateral plate mesoderm","Neural tube"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enotochord\u003C/strong\u003E is a rod-like structure that forms during early embryological development and serves as the primary axis of the embryo. While most of the notochord degenerates, portions persist to form the nuclei pulposi of the intervertebral discs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eparaxial mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the vertebral bodies and arches, but not the nucleus pulposus. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eintermediate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to the urogenital system. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral plate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the heart and limb components. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eneural tube\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vertebral nucleus pulposus develops from the notochord during embryological development.","The notochord is a transient embryonic structure that guides development of the axial skeleton."],"references":["Corallo D, Trapani V, Bonaldo P. The notochord: structure and functions. Cell Mol Life Sci. 2015 Aug;72(16):2989-3008. doi: 10.1007/s00018-015-1897-z. Epub 2015 Apr 2. PMID: 25833128; PMCID: PMC11114051.","de Bree K, de Bakker BS, Oostra RJ. The development of the human notochord. PLoS One. 2018 Oct 22;13(10):e0205752. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0205752. PMID: 30346967; PMCID: PMC6197658.","Torchia, M. G., \u0026 Persaud, T. V. N. (2020). Concise Clinical Embryology: an Integrated, Case-Based Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55884"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15629"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRev